  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is subject to legal prosecution. In most jurisdictions, including China, money laundering is a serious criminal offense. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by disguising its true source. This is typically done through a series of transactions or other financial maneuvers.\n\nIn China, the legal framework for combating money laundering is robust. The Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China, which was enacted in 2007 and amended in recent years, provides the legal basis for addressing money laundering activities. The law mandates that financial institutions and certain non-financial institutions implement strict anti-money laundering (AML) measures, including customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions.\n\nViolations of anti-money laundering regulations can result in severe penalties, including hefty fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment. The Chinese government is committed to combating money laundering and related financial crimes to maintain the integrity of the financial system and uphold the rule of law.",
